<subSubSection id="C33E6525FF92FFC364B3F98D5C61FF43" pageId="10" pageNumber="192" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF92FFC364B3F98D587EFC9A" blockId="10.[151,1437,393,1175]" box="[151,351,393,419]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">DESCRIPTION:</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF92FFC364E3F9A958E7FCFE" blockId="10.[151,1437,393,1175]" box="[199,454,428,455]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC364E3F9A95875FCFF" box="[199,340,428,454]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Wing length</emphasis>
: 5.0 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF92FFC364E3F9D55BFBFF37" blockId="10.[151,1437,393,1175]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC364E3F9D55827FCD3" box="[199,262,465,490]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Wing</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="131F2A2BFF92FFC3653CF9D45852FCD2" box="[280,371,464,491]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="9.[151,264,2007,2031]" captionTargetBox="[156,1425,1481,1975]" captionTargetId="figure-208@9.[151,1436,1474,1984]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 9. Anopheles tenebrosus: a, wing; b, hindleg (from Gillies &amp; de Meillon 1968)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521624" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521624/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Fig. 9a</figureCitation>
): Similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D2DFF92FFC36629F9D55B8FFCD3" authorityName="Grunberg" authorityYear="1902" box="[525,686,465,491]" class="Insecta" family="Culicidae" genus="Anopheles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="192" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ziemanni">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC36629F9D55B8FFCD3" box="[525,686,465,491]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">An. ziemanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but apical pale fringe spot may be reduced, subcostal pale spot sometimes absent, and rarely, costa entirely dark.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF92FFC364E3FA1C5A2EFF0B" blockId="10.[151,1437,393,1175]" box="[199,783,536,563]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC364E3FA1C58B1FF0B" box="[199,400,536,562]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Maxillary palpus</emphasis>
: Shaggy, with four pale bands.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF92FFC364E3FA395C61FF43" blockId="10.[151,1437,393,1175]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC364E3FA395820FF6F" box="[199,257,573,598]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Legs</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="131F2A2BFF92FFC36530FA385853FF6E" box="[276,370,572,599]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="9.[151,264,2007,2031]" captionTargetBox="[156,1425,1481,1975]" captionTargetId="figure-208@9.[151,1436,1474,1984]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 9. Anopheles tenebrosus: a, wing; b, hindleg (from Gillies &amp; de Meillon 1968)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521624" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521624/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Fig. 9b</figureCitation>
): Apex of foretibia and base of foretarsomere 1 always dark. Apex of hindtibia narrowly pale; hindtarsomere 1 entirely dark basally; hindtarsomeres 4 and 5 pale, 0.5 of hindtarsomere 3 pale.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33E6525FF92FFC364E3FA815811FEDB" pageId="10" pageNumber="192" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF92FFC364E3FA815C7DFE33" blockId="10.[151,1437,393,1175]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">
LARVAL HABITAT: Natural collections of clear water with aquatic and semi-aquatic vegetation, such as swamps, ponds, backwaters of streams, springs, ditches and rice fields. In laboratory experiments, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF92FFC364B3FAC958E3FFDE" author="Coetzee, M. &amp; Le Sueur, D." box="[151,450,716,743]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192" pagination="385 - 390" refId="ref7776" refString="Coetzee, M. &amp; Le Sueur, D. (1988) Effects of salinity on the larvae of some Afrotropical anopheline mosquitoes. Medical and Veterinary Entomology, 2 (4), 385 - 390. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2915.1988. tb 00212. x" type="journal article" year="1988">Coetzee &amp; le Sueur (1988)</bibRefCitation>
showed that 39.5% of 1,710 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D2DFF92FFC3672CFAC95A8FFFDF" authorityName="Donitz" authorityYear="1902" box="[776,942,716,743]" class="Insecta" family="Culicidae" genus="Anopheles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="192" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenebrosus">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC3672CFAC95A8FFFDF" box="[776,942,716,743]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">An. tenebrosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
eggs survived to fourth-instar larvae in 25% seawater, suggesting that the species could occupy a broader range of larval habitats than previously thought.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF92FFC364E3FB115811FEDB" blockId="10.[151,1437,393,1175]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">
ADULT BIOLOGY: Cattle-feeding tendencies were confirmed in 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF92FFC3678BFB105D2FFE17" box="[943,1038,788,814]" name="Ethiopia" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Ethiopia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF92FFC36039FB105C3CFE16" author="Habtewold, T. &amp; Prior A. &amp; Torr, S. J. &amp; Gibson, G." box="[1053,1309,788,815]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192" pagination="408 - 417" refId="ref8806" refString="Habtewold, T., Prior A., Torr, S. J. &amp; Gibson, G. (2004) Could insecticide-treated cattle reduce Afrotropical malaria transmission? Effects of deltamethrin-treated Zebu on Anopheles arabiensis behaviour and survival in Ethiopia. Medical and Veterinary Entomology, 18 (4), 408 - 417. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 0269 - 283 X. 2004.00525. x" type="journal article" year="2004">
Habtewold 
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC36085FB115DFBFE17" box="[1185,1242,788,814]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">et al.</emphasis>
2004
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF92FFC3610CFB1159F5FE6A" author="Zeru, M. A. &amp; Shibru, S. &amp; Massebo, F." pageId="10" pageNumber="192" pagination="322" refId="ref12226" refString="Zeru, M. A., Shibru, S. &amp; Massebo, F. (2020) Exploring the impact of cattle on human exposure to malaria mosquitoes in the Arba Minch area district of southwest Ethiopia. Parasites &amp; Vectors, 13, 322. https: // doi. org / 10.1186 / s 13071 - 020 - 04194 - z" type="journal article" year="2020">
Zeru 
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC36140FB115CBCFE17" box="[1380,1437,788,814]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">et al.</emphasis>
2020
</bibRefCitation>
). Long considered unimportant in the transmission of malaria parasites, this was confirmed by recent studies in 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF92FFC36490FB5959D6FE4E" box="[180,247,861,887]" name="Egypt" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Egypt</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF92FFC36522FB5958F0FE4E" author="Morsy, T. A. &amp; El Kadry, A. A. &amp; Salama, M. M. &amp; Sabry, A. H. &amp; El Sharkawy, I. M." box="[262,465,860,887]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192" pagination="213 - 244" refId="ref10043" refString="Morsy, T. A., El Kadry, A. A., Salama, M. M., Sabry, A. H. &amp; El Sharkawy, I. M. (1995) Studies on the bionomics and vector competence of adult anopheline mosquitoes in El Faiyum Governorate, Egypt. Journal of the Egyptian Society of Parasitology, 25 (1), 213 - 244." type="journal article" year="1995">
Morsy 
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC3657CFB5958ABFE4F" box="[344,394,860,886]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">et al</emphasis>
. 1995
</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF92FFC36635FB585B84FE4F" box="[529,677,860,886]" name="Mozambique" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Mozambique</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF92FFC36697FB585A95FE4E" author="Charlwood, J. D. &amp; Macia, G. A. &amp; Manhaca, M. &amp; Sousa, B. &amp; Cuamba, N. &amp; Braganca, M." box="[691,948,860,887]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192" pagination="309 - 320" refId="ref7311" refString="Charlwood, J. D., Macia, G. A., Manhaca, M., Sousa, B., Cuamba, N. &amp; Braganca, M. (2013) Population dynamics and spatial structure of human-biting mosquitoes, inside and outside of houses, in the Chockwe irrigation scheme, southern Mozambique. Geospatial Health, 7 (2), 309 - 320. https: // doi. org / 10.4081 / gh. 2013.89" type="journal article" year="2013">
Charlwood 
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC3671DFB595A4BFE4F" box="[825,874,860,886]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">et al</emphasis>
. 2013
</bibRefCitation>
; S. Irish, personal communication). 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF92FFC3616EFB585803FEA2" author="Aranda, C. &amp; Aponte, J. J. &amp; Saute, F. &amp; Casimiro, S. &amp; Pinto, J. &amp; Sousa, C. &amp; Rosario, V. D. &amp; Petrarca, V. &amp; Dgedge, M. &amp; Alonso, P." pageId="10" pageNumber="192" pagination="180 - 186" refId="ref6730" refString="Aranda, C., Aponte, J. J., Saute, F., Casimiro, S., Pinto, J., Sousa, C., Rosario, V. D., Petrarca, V., Dgedge, M. &amp; Alonso, P. (2005) Entomological characteristics of malaria transmission in Manhica, a rural area in southern Mozambique. Journal of Medical Entomology, 42 (2), 180 - 186. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / jmedent / 42.2.180" type="journal article" year="2005">
Aranda 
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC364B3FB8559F1FEA3" box="[151,208,896,922]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">et al.</emphasis>
(2005)
</bibRefCitation>
in southern 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF92FFC3658BFB845B62FEA3" box="[431,579,896,922]" name="Mozambique" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Mozambique</collectingCountry>
collected 43 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D2DFF92FFC366FFFB855AA1FEA3" authorityName="Donitz" authorityYear="1902" box="[731,896,896,923]" class="Insecta" family="Culicidae" genus="Anopheles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="192" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenebrosus">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC366FFFB855AA1FEA3" box="[731,896,896,923]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">An. tenebrosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in a light trap and reported “a few” positive for circumsporozoite protein “albeit with low optical density values”. No further data were provided, and this requires confirmation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33E6525FF92FFC364E3FBE95D46F9AE" pageId="10" pageNumber="192" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF92FFC364E3FBE95D46F9AE" blockId="10.[151,1437,393,1175]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">
DISTRIBUTION: Widespread and abundant throughout eastern and southern Africa, including 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF92FFC364B3FC1459D7F913" box="[151,246,1040,1066]" name="Angola" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Angola</collectingCountry>
. The presence of 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D2DFF92FFC365ECFC155B5CF913" authorityName="Donitz" authorityYear="1902" box="[456,637,1040,1067]" class="Insecta" family="Culicidae" genus="Anopheles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="192" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenebrosus">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC365ECFC155B5CF913" box="[456,637,1040,1067]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">An. tenebrosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF92FFC36686FC145BD5F913" box="[674,756,1040,1066]" name="Gabon" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Gabon</collectingCountry>
was confirmed by 
